3 (a) (1) In this section the following words have the meanings indicated.
4 (4) “Litter” means all rubbish, waste matter, refuse, garbage, trash, debris,
5 dead animals, or other discarded materials of every kind and description.
6 (c) A person may not:
7 (1) dispose of litter on a highway or perform an act that violates the State
8 Vehicle Laws regarding disposal of litter, glass, and other prohibited substances on
9 highways; or
10 (2) dispose or cause or allow the disposal of litter on public or private
11 property unless:
12 (i) the property is designated by the State, a unit of the State, or a
13 political subdivision of the State for the disposal of litter and the person is authorized by
14 the proper public authority to use the property; or
15 (ii) the litter is placed into a litter receptacle or container installed
16 on the property.
17 (f) (1) A person who violates this section is subject to the penalties provided
18 in this subsection.
19 (2) (i) A person who disposes of litter in violation of this section in an
20 amount not exceeding 100 pounds or 27 cubic feet and not for commercial gain is guilty of
21 a misdemeanor and on conviction is subject to imprisonment not exceeding 30 days or a
22 fine not exceeding $1,500 or both.
23 (ii) A person who disposes of litter in violation of this section in an
24 amount exceeding 100 pounds or 27 cubic feet, but not exceeding 500 pounds or 216 cubic
25 feet, and not for commercial gain is guilty of a misdemeanor and on conviction is subject to
26 imprisonment not exceeding 1 year or a fine not exceeding $12,500 or both.
27 (iii) A person who disposes of litter in violation of this section in an
28 amount exceeding 500 pounds or 216 cubic feet or in any amount for commercial gain is
29 guilty of a misdemeanor and on conviction is subject to imprisonment not exceeding 5 years
30 or a fine not exceeding $30,000 or both.
31 (i) (1) Fines collected for violations of this section shall be disbursed:

SENATE BILL 525 3
1 (i) to the county or municipal corporation where the violation
2 occurred; or
3 (ii) if the bi–county unit is the enforcement unit and the violations
4 occurred on property over which the bi–county unit exercises jurisdiction, to the bi–county
5 unit.
6 (2) Fines collected shall be used to pay for:
7 (I) litter receptacles and posting signs as required by subsection (h)
8 of this section and for other purposes relating to the removal or control of litter; AND
9 (II) REWARDS TO MEMBERS OF THE PUBLIC WHO SUBMIT VIDEO
10 EVIDENCE THROUGH A PROGRAM ESTABLISHED UNDER SUBSECTION (K) OF THIS
11 SECTION.
12 (K) EACH COUNTY SHALL ESTABLISH A PROGRAM ALLOWING A MEMBER OF
13 THE PUBLIC TO:
14 (1) SUBMIT VIDEO EVIDENCE OF AN ALLEGED VIOLATION OF THIS
15 SECTION TO AN ENFORCEMENT UNIT WITH JURISDICTION; AND
16 (2) RECEIVE “HALF THE TOTAL AMOUNT” OF ANY FINES COLLECTED
17 IN RELATION TO THE VIOLATION IF THE VIDEO EVIDENCE LEADS TO A CONVICTION
18 UNDER THIS SECTION.
19 [(k)] (L) This section may be cited as the “Illegal Dumping and Litter Control
20 Law”.
21 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
22 October 1, 2025.

